{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"cb1d64f1-b665-4483-a9ea-2d0b8832bc8e","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**.\n\nAfter a .NET SDK update, your workload manifests and packs may no longer match the new SDK version. `dotnet workload update` pulls the latest versions of all installed workloads, aligning them with your current SDK.\n\n`dotnet workload repair` only *reinstalls* workloads at their current versions — it fixes corrupted or partially-installed packs but won't bring them up to date.\n\n**TL;DR:**\n\n| Command | When to use |\n|---------|-------------|\n| `workload update` | Workloads are outdated (e.g., after SDK update) |\n| `workload repair` | Workloads are corrupted or partially installed |\n\nIf the build still fails after updating, run `dotnet workload restore` in your project directory — it will install any workloads declared in your project/solution that may be missing entirely.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d0bf4748-47e7-456b-aa0f-dbe85a9c6abc","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` to fix a build issue after a .NET SDK update. This is a general knowledge question — I don't need to look at any files or run any commands.\n\nLet me answer from my knowledge:\n\n- `dotnet workload update` — Updates all installed workloads to the latest available versions. This is what you want after an SDK update, since it pulls workload manifests and packs that match your new SDK.\n- `dotnet workload repair` — Reinstalls all installed workloads. Useful if workload files are corrupted or partially installed, but it doesn't update them to newer versions.\n\n\n- For this specific scenario where workloads became outdated following an SDK upgrade, `dotnet workload update` is the right command to run.","outputTokens":410,"requestId":"0839:3596A1:A196AC:BAE566:69F2A773"},"id":"30a09e5e-e608-4734-9e28-6325e489ed07","timestamp":"2026-04-30T00:51:10.033Z"